    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h3>The Power of Regular Contributions</h3>
      <p>
        Compound interest becomes even more powerful when you add <strong>regular recurring
        contributions</strong>. Starting from the same initial capital of &euro;10,000 at 7%
        annual return, but adding <strong>&euro;200 per month</strong>, the results change
        dramatically: after 10 years the capital rises to approximately <strong>&euro;54,130</strong>
        (of which &euro;34,000 comes from contributions and &euro;10,130 from interest earned),
        after 20 years it reaches approximately <strong>&euro;142,400</strong> (with &euro;58,000
        in contributions and &euro;74,400 in interest alone), and after 30 years the total exceeds
        <strong>&euro;319,000</strong>, of which over &euro;237,000 comes exclusively from
        compound interest.
      </p>
      <p>
        These numbers illustrate a fundamental principle: over the long term, the contribution from
        compound interest far exceeds that of the actual deposits made. At 30 years, interest
        represents nearly <strong>75%</strong> of the final capital. This means that time is the
        most valuable asset for any investor: the sooner you start investing consistently, the
        greater the multiplying effect of your money. Even small monthly amounts, maintained with
        discipline over long horizons, can generate substantial wealth.
      </p>

